# No Persian Comments Rule

## Rule
**NEVER write comments in Persian/Farsi language in code files.**

## Guidelines
- All code comments must be written in English only
- Variable names, function names, and identifiers should be in English
- Error messages and console logs should be in English
- Documentation strings should be in English
- Only user-facing text (UI labels, messages) can be in Persian

## Examples

### ❌ Wrong (Persian comments)
```javascript
// تعیین وضعیت پرداخت بر اساس URL parameters
const paymentStatus = getUrlParam("ps");

// اگر پارامترهای سپ موجود باشد، منتظر پاسخ سپ می‌مانیم
if (sepToken || sepRefNum) {
  // ...
}
```

### ✅ Correct (English comments)
```javascript
// Determine payment status based on URL parameters
const paymentStatus = getUrlParam("ps");

// If SEP parameters exist, wait for SEP response
if (sepToken || sepRefNum) {
  // ...
}
```

## Exceptions
- User-facing text in UI components (labels, messages, placeholders)
- Configuration files that specifically require Persian text
- Documentation files (README.md, etc.) can contain Persian if needed for user understanding

## Enforcement
This rule applies to all code files including:
- JavaScript/TypeScript files (.js, .ts, .jsx, .tsx)
- CSS/SCSS files
- Configuration files
- Any other code-related files

Always use English for technical documentation and code comments to maintain consistency and readability for international developers.